'''Leandro Jones Johan Bacuna''' (born 21 August 1991) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] or [[Defender (association football)#Full back|right-back]] for [[TFF 1. Lig|TFF First League]] club [[Iğdır F.K.|Iğdır FK]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=LEANDRO JONES JOHAN BACUNA - Player Details TFF |url=https://www.tff.org/Default.aspx?pageId=526&kisiId=2820673 |access-date=2026-02-07 |website=www.tff.org}}</ref> Born in the Netherlands, he represents the [[Curaçao national football team|Curaçao national team]]. He is their joint [[Curaçao national football team#Most appearances|most-capped player]] along with [[Eloy Room]].

==Club career==

===Groningen===
On 30 October 2009, Bacuna made his first team debut for [[FC Groningen|Groningen]] in an [[Eredivisie]] match against [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vi.nl/Spelers/Speler.htm?employer=57&season=382&dbid=63150&typeofpage=84137|title=Cookies op VI.nl}}</ref> Bacuna has also played for Groningen's youth teams. On 6 November 2009, he scored his first goal for the first team in a league match against [[Heracles Almelo]], an eventual 4–1 victory for Groningen.<ref>[http://politiken.dk/sport/fodbold/article815651.ece Holland, Æresdivisionen&nbsp;– Politiken.dk] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091027031438/http://politiken.dk/sport/fodbold/article815651.ece |date=27 October 2009 }}</ref>

===Aston Villa===
It was announced on 13 June 2013 that Bacuna had signed a three-year contract with [[Premier League]] club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]. Handed the number 7 shirt, Bacuna impressed many with his debut season for the Villains, despite constantly playing out of position at right back.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2013-06-13 |title=Groninger Bacuna wordt collega van Vlaar in Engeland |url=https://www.vi.nl/nieuws/groninger-bacuna-wordt-collega-van-vlaar-in-engeland |access-date=2024-03-05 |website=Voetbal International |language=nl}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=2013-06-13 |title=Bacuna tipped to be "a real asset" after sealing Villa transfer |url=http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10265~3209128,00.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615161605/http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10265~3209128%2C00.html |archive-date=15 June 2013 |website=AVFC}}</ref> Bacuna scored his first Premier League goal on 28 September at home against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. His second goal came from a free-kick in the claret and blues' 2–0 victory over [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]. He continued his goalscoring run with goals against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C|West Bromwich Albion]], [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich]]. {{citation needed|date=December 2014}}

In the [[2014–15 Aston Villa F.C. season|2014–15 season]], Bacuna found it harder to break into the starting line-up, starting just one game in the [[2014–15 Premier League|Premier League]]. On 15 February 2015, he scored the first of two Villa goals in the fifth round of the [[2014–15 FA Cup|FA Cup]] in a 2–1 win over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], taking the club into the quarter-finals.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}

On 20 August 2015, Bacuna signed a new long-term contract with the club.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2015-08-20 |title=Leandro Bacuna: New long-term Aston Villa deal for Dutchman |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34006797 |access-date=2026-01-05 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

===Reading===
On 13 August 2017, Bacuna moved to [[Reading F.C.|Reading]], signing a four-year contract.<ref name="Reading Sign Bacuna">{{cite web|title=Bacuna joins the Royals!|url=https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2017/august/bacuna-joins-the-royals/|publisher=Reading F.C.|access-date=13 August 2017|date=13 August 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Reading in an [[EFL Cup]] tie against [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] on 22 August 2017.<ref>{{cite web 
|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40932153
|title=Reading 3–1 Millwall
|publisher=BBC
|date=22 August 2017 |access-date=29 August 2017}}</ref>

===Cardiff City===
On 31 January 2019, Bacuna moved to Premier League side [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], signing a four-and-a-half-year deal for a transfer fee believed to be around £3 million.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cardiffcityfc.co.uk/news/2019/january/deadline-day-bacuna-is-a-bluebird/ |title=Deadline Day: Bacuna is a Bluebird |publisher=Cardiff City F.C. |date=31 January 2019 |access-date=31 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/cardiff-city-transfer-news-deadline-day-rumours-today-epl-leandro-bacuna-a8757036.html |title=Leandro Bacuna signs in £3m deal from Reading |newspaper=The Independent |last=Blanche |first=Phil |date=31 January 2019 |access-date=31 January 2019}}</ref> On 10 June 2022, Cardiff announced Bacuna would leave the club when his contract expired on 30 June.<ref>{{Cite web |title=2021/22 Retained List {{!}} Cardiff |url=https://www.cardiffcityfc.co.uk/news/202122-retained-list |access-date=10 June 2022 |website=www.cardiffcityfc.co.uk |language=en}}</ref>

===Watford===
On 14 December 2022, Bacuna signed for Championship club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on a contract until the end of the [[2022–23 Watford F.C. season|2022–23 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.watfordfc.com/news/official-bacuna-signs-on|title=Official: Bacuna Signs On|website=www.watfordfc.com|date=14 December 2022|accessdate=14 December 2022}}</ref>

===Iğdır FK===
On 6 January 2026, he was transferred to [[Iğdır F.K.|Iğdır FK]], signing a one and half year contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alagöz Holding Iğdır Futbol Kulübü |url=https://x.com/igdirFK/status/2008591366289227821 |website=X |access-date=11 January 2026}}</ref>

==International career==
Born in the Netherlands to parents of Afro-Curaçaoan descent, Bacuna played for the [[Netherlands Antilles national football team|Netherlands Antilles under-20]] side, as well as various youth Dutch teams. He received his first [[Curaçao national football team|Curaçao national team]] call-up in March 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2016/03/17/aston-villa-defender-leandro-bacuna-gets-first-senior-internatio/|title=Aston Villa defender Leandro Bacuna gets first senior international call-up for Curacao}}</ref> earning his first cap in a 1–0 loss to [[Barbados national football team|Barbados]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://readastonvilla.com/2016/03/28/villans-international-duty-part-1-2/|title=Villans on international duty – Part One|date=28 March 2016}}</ref>
{{clear}}

==Personal life==
He is the older brother of fellow professional football player [[Juninho Bacuna]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nos.nl/artikel/2036079-ook-tweede-bacuna-wint-de-beker.html|title=Ook tweede Bacuna wint de beker|language=Dutch}}</ref>

